  "solution": [
    "## Solutions to Linear and Quadratic Functions Exercises",
    "",
    "### Exercise 1: Linear Functions - Basic Properties",
    "",
    "**a)** Slope m = 2, y-intercept b = 1, line through (0,1) with slope 2",
    "",
    "**b)** y - 3 = 2(x - 1) → y = 2x + 1",
    "",
    "**c)** Slope m = -3, y-intercept b = 6, x-intercept: x = 2",
    "",
    "**d)** y + 1 = (1/2)(x - 2) → y = (1/2)x - 2",
    "",
    "**e)** Yes, degree 1 polynomial",
    "",
    "### Exercise 2: Linear Functions - Point-Slope Form",
    "",
    "**a)** Slope = (9-5)/(4-2) = 2, y - 5 = 2(x - 2) → y = 2x + 1",
    "",
    "**b)** Slope = (-1-3)/(3+1) = -1, y - 3 = -1(x + 1) → y = -x + 2",
    "",
    "**c)** Slope = 2/3, y = (2/3)x",
    "",
    "**d)** Slope = (3-1)/(-1-1) = 1, y - 1 = 1(x - 1) → y = x + 0",
    "",
    "**e)** Slope = (d-b)/(c-a), y - b = m(x - a)",
    "",
    "### Exercise 3: Linear Functions - Parallel and Perpendicular",
    "",
    "**a)** Parallel lines have same slope 2, y - 4 = 2(x - 3) → y = 2x - 2",
    "",
    "**b)** Perpendicular slope = 2, y - 2 = 2(x - 1) → y = 2x",
    "",
    "**c)** Parallel to 3x + 2y = 6 (slope -3/2), through (0,0): y = (-3/2)x",
    "",
    "**d)** Perpendicular slope = 1/2, y - 1 = (1/2)(x - 2) → y = (1/2)x",
    "",
    "**e)** All have slope m, different intercepts",
    "",
    "### Exercise 4: Quadratic Functions - Standard Form",
    "",
    "**a)** Vertex (0,0), axis x=0, opens upward",
    "",
    "**b)** Vertex (2,1), axis x=2, opens upward",
    "",
    "**c)** Vertex (-1,-3), axis x=-1, opens upward",
    "",
    "**d)** Vertex (2, 3), axis x=2, opens downward",
    "",
    "**e)** Vertex (1,2), axis x=1, opens upward, stretched by factor 3",
    "",
    "### Exercise 5: Quadratic Functions - General Form",
    "",
    "**a)** x² - 4x + 3 = (x-2)² - 1, vertex (2,-1)",
    "",
    "**b)** 2(x² + 4x + 4) + 6 - 8 = 2(x+2)² - 2, vertex (-2,-2)",
    "",
    "**c)** -(x² - 6x + 9) - 5 + 9 = -(x-3)² + 4, vertex (3,4)",
    "",
    "**d)** (x+1)², vertex (-1,0)",
    "",
    "**e)** 3(x² - 4x + 4) + 7 - 12 = 3(x-2)² - 5, vertex (2,-5)",
    "",
    "### Exercise 6: Quadratic Functions - Roots and Factors",
    "",
    "**a)** Roots: x = 2, 3; factors: (x-2)(x-3)",
    "",
    "**b)** Roots: x = 3, -4; factors: (x-3)(x+4)",
    "",
    "**c)** Roots: x = 1, 3/2; factors: 2(x-1)(x-3/2)",
    "",
    "**d)** Roots: x = 2, -2; factors: (x-2)(x+2)",
    "",
    "**e)** D = 1 - 4 = -3 < 0, complex roots",
    "",
    "### Exercise 7: Quadratic Functions - Maximum/Minimum",
    "",
    "**a)** Vertex (2, 5), maximum value 5",
    "",
    "**b)** Vertex (2, -10), minimum value -10",
    "",
    "**c)** Vertex (-2,5), maximum value 5",
    "",
    "**d)** Vertex (-1, 2), minimum value 2, range [2, ∞)",
    "",
    "**e)** Vertex (2, 5), maximum value 5",
    "",
    "### Exercise 8: Quadratic Functions - Applications",
    "",
    "**a)** f(x) = x² + x + 0, through (1,2): 1+1+0=2 ✓, (2,5):4+2+0=6≠5, wait: f(x)=x²+x-1",
    "",
    "**b)** f(x) = a(x-2)² + 3, through (0,7): a(4) + 3 = 7 → 4a=4 → a=1",
    "",
    "**c)** Roots 1,3: f(x)=a(x-1)(x-3), vertex (2,-1): a(1)(-1)=-1 → a=1",
    "",
    "**d)** Max height 121 ft at t=2.5s, hits ground at t=5.06s",
    "",
    "**e)** Max revenue $2500 at x=50 items",
    "",
    "### Exercise 9: Systems with Linear and Quadratic",
    "",
    "**a)** x² = x + 2 → x² - x - 2 = 0 → (x-2)(x+1)=0 → x=-1,2; points (-1,1), (2,4)",
    "",
    "**b)** x² - 4 = 2x - 1 → x² - 2x - 3 = 0 → (x-3)(x+1)=0 → x=-1,3; points (-1,-5), (3,5)",
    "",
    "**c)** x² + x - 2 = -x + 4 → x² + 2x - 6 = 0 → (x+3)(x-2)=0 → x=-3,2; points (-3,4), (2,0)",
    "",
    "**d)** (x-1)² = x → x² - 2x + 1 = x → x² - 3x + 1 = 0 → x=(3±√5)/2",
    "",
    "**e)** x² = 4 - x² → 2x² = 4 → x² = 2 → x=±√2; points (√2,2), (-√2,2)",
    "",
    "### Exercise 10: Linear vs Quadratic Comparison",
    "",
    "**a)** Quadratic grows faster than linear for large |x|",
    "",
    "**b)** When |x| > |slope|, quadratic dominates",
    "",
    "**c)** Linear intersects parabola at two points generally",
    "",
    "**d)** Linear has constant slope, quadratic has varying slope",
    "",
    "**e)** Linear is asymptotic to infinity, quadratic to ±∞",
    "",
    "### Exercise 11: Quadratic Inequalities",
    "",
    "**a)** (x-2)(x-3) > 0 → x < 2 or x > 3",
    "",
    "**b)** (x+4)(x-2) ≤ 0 → -4 ≤ x ≤ 2",
    "",
    "**c)** 2(x-1)(x-3/2) < 0 → 1 < x < 3/2",
    "",
    "**d)** (x-2)(x+2) ≥ 0 → x ≤ -2 or x ≥ 2",
    "",
    "**e)** -(x-2)² + 1 ≤ 0 → (x-2)² ≥ 1 → x ≤ 1 or x ≥ 3",
    "",
    "### Exercise 12: Linear Inequalities",
    "",
    "**a)** x > 4/2 = 2",
    "",
    "**b)** -x ≤ 5 → x ≥ -5",
    "",
    "**c)** 2x < 10 → x < 5",
    "",
    "**d)** 2x ≥ -4 → x ≥ -2",
    "",
    "**e)** -5x > -8 → x < 8/5",
    "",
    "### Exercise 13: Combined Linear-Quadratic Inequalities",
    "",
    "**a)** x² - x > 0 → x(x-1) > 0 → x < 0 or x > 1",
    "",
    "**b)** -4 ≤ x ≤ 3 and x > 0 → 0 < x ≤ 3",
    "",
    "**c)** x² - 2x - 3 < 0 → (x-3)(x+1) < 0 → -1 < x < 3",
    "",
    "**d)** (x-1)(x-3) ≥ 0 → x ≤ 1 or x ≥ 3",
    "",
    "**e)** -2 ≤ x ≤ 2 and x ≥ -1 → -1 ≤ x ≤ 2",
    "",
